"Yes, sir. They should be on their way now, we've given them time to pack up from the mess hall." 05:00 hours, Exodus linked up with the motor pool. Lieutenant Shaw stood on a crate, beginning to speak.
"We will proceed to the forward operating base on I-131, 50 miles outside Ialos City. We will be supporting the ongoing siege operation, then attack Ialos City and clear out the rebels in the area. We will use this as a staging area and push into the mountains." Lieutenant Shaw explained. "Take your squad and get ready to move out."
The squad scattered, each platoon breaking off to board a tank under the command of their platoon sergeants. Colonel Corey climbed aboard the lead tank in the convoy, accompanied by Nimitz, Kress, and two new recruits.
"Hey, Colonel, is Harris still got Snowball?" Nimitz asked after they settled in.
"Are you talking about that chicken he stole?" Colonel Corey remembered the scene of them stealing chickens from a farm that morning. "Yes, I'm sure of it."
Colonel Corey glanced at another tank, and saw Harris and his men. He caught a glimpse of a small chicken peeking out from behind Harris's backpack.
"Yes, he's still got that chicken." Colonel Corey replied, as the hatch of the turret swung open and the driver appeared before them.
"All tanks have departed," the driver said calmly and clearly into his radio.
About an hour later, a new recruit (Colonel Corey remembered he was called Osborn) spoke up and asked, "Lieutenant, have you been on the front lines since the war started?"
"Right, we've been here since the Storm of Fire operation started," Colonel Corey replied. "We thought we'd be done in a few weeks, but... we underestimated them."
"They've exceeded our expectations in terms of firepower and manpower. They shot down UFS Revenant in the first two weeks, and last month they took out Erebus. Dammit, we should be able to see it on the road."
"Alright, I'll fight bravely for the Federation." Osborn declared firmly, "I won't be intimidated by those terrorists."
"You're saying that now, but from what I've seen, most young recruits like you tend to panic the moment they hear gunfire."
"Let's see," Colonel Corey said with a smile. Osborn remained silent.
"All tanks have departed," the driver said calmly and clearly into his radio.
Colonel Corey climbed onto the tank, putting on his optical goggles. Switching to thermal imaging mode, he saw the heat signal in the distance.
"All tanks have departed, I see them."
"Are they the enemy?" another new recruit, Natalia, asked.
"All tanks have departed," Colonel Corey said calmly and clearly into his radio. "Exodus team, unless attacked, do not fire, draw them out first."
As they drew closer, the faint heat signal from the indistinct blotch became a clearer outline. One of them sprinted off to some location, picked up something, and then ran back to the small ridge. They then lay down, assuming a firing position.
"Enemy contact!" Lieutenant Shaw shouted over the radio as orange tracers shot out from the ridge. Bullets pinged off the side of the tank, and the team members leapt off, taking cover behind the tank. A rocket whizzed in, striking the ground behind the tank column, its explosion sending shrapnel into one of the tanks. Another rocket hit an APS-Cerberus armored personnel carrier on its side, exploding. After the ammo cooked off, the crew members of the armored personnel carrier scrambled out, seeking cover.
"Troop 1-2 and 1-3, right 25 degrees, 300 yards. Fire!" the tank platoon sergeant shouted over the radio.
"Deploy sentry robots!" Lieutenant Knox shouted, observing the ridge through binoculars. A "Hellhound's" rear hatch swung open, and a soldier, unarmed and wearing a customized headset, stepped out. He bellowed orders into a square microphone, and two "Sentry" robots sprang out in response. Their slender metal arms and legs extended, and they sprinted forward at breakneck speed. The robots were armed, but their weapons were slung over their backs.
"Shoot or capture?" Kress asked, observing the situation.
"It looks like they're going to take them alive," Colonel Corey speculated, watching as the two sentry robots disappeared into the smoke and flames.
He struggled to get up, Lieutenant Shaw came over. Lieutenant Shaw turned to one of the sentries. "How many?"
"Three are dead, sir," the sentry robot replied. "The rest have fled on foot."
Lieutenant Shaw nodded, turned and said to Colonel Corey and Kress, who stood nearby, "Can you two take this person away?"
